        "paragraph_index": 0,
        "text": "## Ligand Classes in SRD-46\n\nThere are **60 distinct ligand classes** in the database.\n\nHere are the **five classes with the most ligands**:\n\n| Rank | Ligand Class | Number of Ligands | % of Total |\n|------|--------------------------|-------------------|------------|\n| 1 | Ligands not selected | 1 339 | 23.3% |\n| 2 | Amino Acids | 297 | 5.2% |\n| 3 | Aliphatic amines | 250 | 4.4% |\n| 4 | Pyridines (azines) | 248 | 4.3% |\n| 5 | Carboxylic acids | 182 | 3.2% |\n\n> **Note:** The top class, *\"Ligands not selected,\"* is a catch-all for ligands that have not been assigned to a specific chemical class — it accounts for nearly a quarter of all 5 750 ligands. If we exclude that placeholder, the top five \"real\" classes are **Amino Acids (297)**, **Aliphatic amines (250)**, **Pyridines/azines (248)**, **Carboxylic acids (182)**, and **Aza-macrocycles (165)**. These reflect the dominance of nitrogen- and oxygen-donor ligands in coordination chemistry, which is expected given their strong affinity for a wide range of metal ions.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
